1448. ³¹⁶ JOHN GRENEFELD, of Southwelles, Hants. To be buried at Friars Minors, London, ‘⁴ videlicet in introitu sub campanile coram hostio cancelle eiusdem ecclesie.‘' Bequeathed 205. to the Prior and Convent for his burial. Service by note to be said for his soul in the Choir daily for one month after his decease3 for which purpose he left each friar chaplain in the said church 25. 6d.

Will dated 8 June, 1448. Proved 24 June, 1448. 3 5 Luffenam.

His tomb was in the WalkIng place.

1448. JOHN WYoT, citizen and clothworker. To be buried “in ecclesia Fratrum Minorum, London, juxta tumulum Johannie Assheley, militis.'' His executors were to remunerate the Convent at their discretion.

Will dated 2 5 Sept., 1448. Proved 10 October, 1448. Comm. Lond., Prowet, f. 244.

John Wyot‚ or Wyett, was buried with his wife Margaret in the fifth bay of the Choir in S. Mary's Chapel, on the right hand of Sir John Assheley. Grey Friars, p. 84.
